            . I am a <rs id="t18240603-244-viclabel1267" type="occupation">patent lamp manufacturer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18240603-244-victim2081 t18240603-244-viclabel1267"></join>, and live in Charles-street, Hatton-garden. The prisoner was my <rs id="t18240603-244-deflabel1268" type="occupation">weekly servant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18240603-244-defend2079 t18240603-244-deflabel1268"></join>; in consequence of some information, I went with a publican, named Ranwell, to the prisoner's lodgings, to ascertain whether he had got a pint pot - he had given leave for us to go - the officer, who was with us, could not find the pot, but in the cupboard we found some brass goods, which I knew to be my property - when the officer asked how he came to take them, he said he did not know, and said they were his master's; they are worth about 11 s. - he has lived with me six or seven years, and I thought him honest.</p>
               <p>
            
